title: For Sale:  .75 caliber German wheel-lock Hunting rifle
postcontent: This is a pretty nice example of what is known as a "Muller rifle" which is apparently a sub-dvision of the genre known as German "Jaeger rifles". I've done a bit of research in books and on the net and find that this rifle displays several traits which are common to rifles of the Brandenburg region. It dates to the later decades of the era of wheel-locks (1500-1650) It was produced during the time when cheaper and more user-friendly flint-locks were available but the wheel-lock was considered to have superior ignition than flint-locks; flint-locks having about a 20% failure rate to ignite at the first attempt. The nature and function of the wheel-lock mechanism basically almost insured ignition when the action was set and triggered.The precise manufacturer is unknown. Possibly this model was produced in some numbers rather than being a custom made or unique piece. The butt-plate has an inscribed "No. 38". Is that a serial number or a rack number? I don't know. There are no other markings visible anywhere else on the outside of the gun. I have not; nor do I intend to dismantle the barrel from the stock. Underneath the barrel there could be a world of info or there could be none at all. I've no idea.The metal is in extremely nice condition with the vas majority of it's surface being polished steel. Very little rust or pitting. The arm folds back over the wheel aperture, the trigger sets properly and the small spring operated door which opens the lock aperture functions correctly. I have not wound the lock and attempted to trigger it. Not intending to shoot the piece, I was told that with ancient mechanical devises such as this; it's best not to tempt fate and "screw" with it unless you intend to shoot it.The stock is fairly ornate but lacks the intricate carving and brass, bone or precious metal inlays. I believe it is walnut and remains in sound condition overall. There are a couple of cracks as can be seen in the photos. These could have been repaired at some point as they do not cause any wiggle. The stock appears solid and firm. The patch compartment seals by a carved and dove-tailed wooden slab that closes with a spring latch. All functions correctly and a tight seal is produced when the block is set into the stock and clicked shut.The bore of the weapon is a massive .75 inch caliber and you can see the fascinating method of rifling the bore in an era which pre-dates our American revolution by two centuries. Just looking at this fascinating weapon in this condition; it is difficult to imagine that it was being used to hunt large game in Europe's forests a hundred years before George Washington was even born.Here are some statistics:Overall length 40.25 inchesBarrel length 28.25 inches (including the tang)Ram rod length 26.175 inches (rod protrudes from the barrel by .20 inches when put down the bore)Caliber .75 inchesOverall weight about 8 poundsThis rifle came from an answer to an advertisement for buying old guns and Military items. The man who had it related how his father had brought it home from WW2 in 1946.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Defarbed Euroarms 1861 Springfield
postcontent: I have a Euroarms m1861 Springfield with original bayonet for sale or trade.  This is one of the quality rifles made before Euroarms was bought out.  The rifling is pristine and the action is crisp.  It is a straight shooter.  The stock was reshaped, stamped, and stained to match the originals by Comer Gun Works.  Modern markings were removed from the barrel to make the rifle as close to originial as possible.  The lockplate is the standard "Springfield 1861" as I did not get around to swapping it out with an original or restamped plate.  The sling swivels have not been defarbed either but I just remove them for historical events.  The original bayonet fits well and is nice and straight.  There is a light patina but no pitting or rust.  The rifle has a couple of dark spots on it but is mostly armory bright.  Includes rifle tool and ramrod worm as well as cleaning jag, bullet puller, bore scraper, and nipple driver.I am interested in trades for a defarbed blackpowder shotgun or Colt 2nd Generation 1849 pocket revolver, dragoon revolver, or 1851 navy.  I am also interested in trading for a quality 30-06, preferably a Kimber, Winchester, or Ruger, or for a pre-64 Winchester 1894 30-30 lever action or Henry 30-30 lever action.
